          "body": "The petition against Edom (137:7) is often overlooked beside the notorious verse 9, but it carries its own weight. Edom was not Babylon — Edom was Israel's brother-nation, descended from Esau (Genesis 36:1). The prophet Obadiah devotes an entire book to Edom's betrayal on the day Jerusalem fell: 'On the day that you stood aloof, on the day that strangers carried off his wealth and foreigners entered his gate and cast lots for Jerusalem — you too were like one of them' (Obadiah 11). Edom did not merely fail to help; according to Obadiah 13-14, they blocked the roads and handed over survivors. Their cry, 'Raze it, raze it, to its very foundation!' (137:7), is the cry of a brother turned executioner. The psalmist quotes it verbatim before God — not in bitterness but as evidence in a judicial proceeding. He is presenting the case to the Judge. The petition is: You heard them say it; now remember it and act accordingly."
