          "title": "The imprecatory close — reading verse 9 honestly",
          "body": "Verse 9 is the most disturbing verse in the Psalter for most modern readers: 'How blessed will be the one who seizes and dashes your little ones against the rock.' The history of interpretation runs the full spectrum. Origen allegorized the infants as 'sinful thoughts.' Luther read the psalm messianically — 'Babylon' as the tyranny of the papal system. But the straightforward reading remains necessary before any other move is made: the psalmist is invoking against Babylon precisely what Babylon did to others. Babylonian warfare against captured cities routinely included the slaughter of infants (cf. Isaiah 13:16; Nahum 3:10; 2 Kings 8:12). The psalmist is not inventing a fresh horror — he is applying the lex talionis to the horror already committed. Three things must be held together: First, this is a *prayer*, not an act — the psalmist asks God, not himself, to raise up a repayer. Second, the imprecation is prophetically accurate — Babylon fell to Cyrus the Great in 539 BC, and Isaiah had already predicted it (Isaiah 13:1-22; 47:1-15). Third, the New Testament does not eliminate this category of prayer; it locates it in God's eschatological justice — 'Vengeance is Mine, I will repay, says the Lord' (Romans 12:19; Revelation 6:10 contains a structurally identical imprecatory cry from the souls under the altar). The psalm hands the violence upward; it does not authorize the believer to take it up."
