          "title": "Psalm 137 in the canonical and eschatological horizon",
          "body": "Read canonically, Psalm 137 is not the last word — it is a held breath waiting for the last word. The last word arrives in stages. Historically: Cyrus issued his decree in 538 BC and the exiles returned (Ezra 1:1-4), fulfilling the prophetic promise (Isaiah 44:28; Jeremiah 29:10). Eschatologically: Babylon becomes in the New Testament the archetypal name for every God-opposing empire (Revelation 17-18), and the cry 'How blessed' is answered at the fall of that final Babylon — 'Rejoice over her, O heaven, and you saints and apostles and prophets, because God has pronounced judgment for you against her' (Revelation 18:20). The same theological structure: grief, vow, petition, divine justice. The believer reading Psalm 137 today inhabits a similar tension — between the city of exile and the city of God, between the world as it is and the New Jerusalem as it will be (Revelation 21:2-4). Augustine's reading of the psalm in the *City of God* is unsurpassed: we are pilgrims by rivers of Babylon, and we must not sing the Lord's song as if we were already home. We hang the harps, we remember, we pray for justice — and we wait for the city whose builder and maker is God (Hebrews 11:10)."
